<a name = "ComplexArithmetic"><b> Complex Arithmetic </b></a>
<p>
	Cartesian:
	\[
		C = \{a + bi: a, b\in R\}.
	\]

	Polar form:
	\[
		z = re^{i\theta},
	\]
	where $\theta$ is the argument and $\theta$ is the magnitude.

	The conversion from cartesian representation to polar representation is
	\begin{align*}
		r &= \sqrt{a^2 + b^2},\\
		\theta &= \text{atan2}(a,b) = \arctan\left(\frac{b}{a}\right),
	\end{align*}
	where when we use $\arctan\left(\frac{b}{a}\right)$ we lost 
	some information about the sign of $b/a$, so we might need to plus
	or minus $\pi$.

	The inverse conversion is
	\[ a = r\cos\theta, \]
	\[ b = r\sin\theta. \]
</p>

